"Fukui K., Fujii Y., Ageta Y., Asahi K.","Changes in the lower limit of mountain permafrost between 1973 and 2004 in the Khumbu Himal, the Nepal Himalayas",2007,"Global and Planetary Change","55","4",,"251","256",,,10.1016/j.gloplacha.2006.06.002,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33846230597&partnerID=40&md5=cefb5c00b1cbbf47aa9b4187b8e603b1","National Institute of Polar Research, 1-9-10 Kaga, Itabashi-ku, Tokyo, 173-8515, Japan; Institute for Hydrospheric-Atomospheric Sciences, Nagoya University, Furo-cho, Chikusa-ku, Nagoya, 464-8601, Japan; Faculty of Environmental Earth Science, Hokkaido University, Sapporo, 060-0810, Japan","Fukui, K., National Institute of Polar Research, 1-9-10 Kaga, Itabashi-ku, Tokyo, 173-8515, Japan; Fujii, Y., National Institute of Polar Research, 1-9-10 Kaga, Itabashi-ku, Tokyo, 173-8515, Japan; Ageta, Y., Institute for Hydrospheric-Atomospheric Sciences, Nagoya University, Furo-cho, Chikusa-ku, Nagoya, 464-8601, Japan; Asahi, K., Faculty of Environmental Earth Science, Hokkaido University, Sapporo, 060-0810, Japan","Because the Khumbu Himal of the Nepal Himalayas lacks long-term climate records from weather stations, mountain permafrost degradation serves as an important indicator of climate warming. In 1973, the permafrost lower limit was estimated to be 5200-5300 m above sea level (ASL) on southern-aspect slopes in this region. Using ground-temperature measurements, we examined the mountain permafrost lower limit on slopes with the same aspect in 2004. The results indicate that the permafrost lower limit was 5400-5500 m ASL in 2004. The permafrost lower limit was estimated to be 5400 to 5500 m on slopes with a southern aspect in the Khumbu Himal in 1991 using seismic reflection soundings. Thus, it is possible that the permafrost lower limit has risen 100-300 m between 1973 and 1991, followed by a stable limit of 5400 to 5500 m over the last decade. An increase in mean annual air temperature of approximately 0.2 to 0.4 °C from the 1970s to the 1990s has indicated a rise in the permafrost lower limit of 40 to 80 m at the Tibetan Plateau. The rise in the mountain permafrost lower limit in the Khumbu Himal exceeds that of the Tibetan Plateau, suggesting the possibility of greater climate warming in the Khumbu Himal. © 2006 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","global warming; ground temperature; permafrost; the Khumbu Himal; the Nepal Himalayas","air temperature; global warming; ground-based measurement; permafrost; seismic reflection; Asia; Eurasia; Himalayas; Khumbu Himal; Nepal; South Asia",,,,,,"Asahi, K., Inventory and recent variations of glaciers in the eastern Nepal Himalayas (2001) Seppyo, 63, pp. 159-169. , (in Japanese); Barsch, D., Jakob, M., Active rockglaciers and the lower limit of discontinuous alpine permafrost in the Khumbu Himalaya, Nepal (1993) Proceedings of the Sixth International Conference on Permafrost, pp. 27-31. , South China University of Technology Press, Beijing; Bollasina, M., Bertolani, L., Tartari, G., Meteorological observations at high altitude in the Khumbu Valley, Nepal Himalayas, 1994-1999 (2002) Bull. Glacier Res., 19, pp. 1-11; Fujii, Y., Higuchi, K., On the permafrost at the summit of Mt. Fuji (1972) Seppyo, 34, pp. 9-22. , (in Japanese); Fujii, Y., Higuchi, K., Ground temperature and its relation to permafrost occurrences in the Khumbu Himal and Hidden Valley (1976) Seppyo, 38, pp. 125-128; Fujii, Y., Masuzawa, T., Hashimoto, T., Onoda, M., Ueno, K., Change of the permafrost lower limit at Mt. Fuji in 1976-1998 (1999) Reprints of the 1999 Conference Japanese Society of Snow and Ice, 36. , (in Japanese); Fujita, K., Nakawo, M., Fujii, Y., Paudyal, P., Changes in glaciers in Hidden Valley, Mukut Himal, Nepal Himalayas, from 1974 to 1994 (1997) J. Glaciol., 42, pp. 583-588; Gorbunov, A., Monitoring the evolution of permafrost in the Tien Shan (1996) Permafr. Periglac. Process., 7, pp. 297-298; Grabs, W.E., Pokhrel, A.P., Establishment of a measu